  42 | {|||}      | \item[C.] \textbf{Differential equation}
  43 | {|||}      | 
  44 | {|||}      | 
  45 | {|||}      | Population is $u(t)$. What is the \textbf{rate of change} of the
  46 | {|||}      | population?
  47 | {|||}      | 
  48 | {|||}      | In a time interval $\delta t$:
  49 | {|||}      | \begin{itemize}
  50 | {|||}      | \item A proportion $a \delta t$ of population produce
  51 | {|||}      | children.
  52 | {|||}      | 
  53 | {|||}      | \item A proportion $b \delta t$ of population die.
  54 | {|||}      | 
  55 | {|||}      | \item A proportion $c \delta t$ of population emigrate to Mars.
  56 | {|||}      | \end{itemize}
  57 | {|||}      | 
  58 | {|||}      | So,
  59 | {|||}      | \begin{align*}
  60 | {|||}      | & u(t + \delta t)  =  u(t) + (a-b-c)u(t) \delta t  \\
  61 | {|||}      | \Longrightarrow & \dfrac{u(t+\delta t) - u(t)}{\delta t} =
  62 | {|||}      | \lambda u(t),
  63 | {|||}      | \end{align*}
  64 | {|||}      | where $\lambda = a - b - c$.
  65 | {|||}      | 
  66 | {|||}      | \end{description}
  67 | {|||}      | 
  68 | {|||}      | Let $\delta t \to 0$ (see analysis course).
  69 | {|||}      | 
  70 | {|||}      | Then
  71 | {|||}      |   \begin{align*}
  72 | {|||}      |     \dfrac{du(t)}{dt} & =  \lambda u(t)  \\
  73 | {|||}      |     u(t_{0}) & = u_{0}
  74 | {|||}      |   \end{align*}
  75 | {|||}      | 
  76 | {|||}      | A differential equation like this, describing population growth, was used by Thomas Malthus, early 19th century.
  77 | {|||}      | 
  78 | {|||}      | \subsection*{Parameter estimation}
  79 | {|||}      | 
  80 | {|||}      | The UN estimates that the population grows by $1.14\%$ per year.
  81 | {|||}      | 
  82 | {|||}      | Let $t$ be time in years.
  83 | {|||}      | 
  84 | {|||}      | We separate the variables in our differential equation, then integrate (details later, when we study differential equations).
  85 | {|||}      |   \begin{align*}
  86 | {|||}      |     \dfrac{du}{dt} & = \lambda u  \\
  87 | {|||}      |     \implies \int \dfrac{1}{u} \, du & = \int \lambda \, dt  \\
  88 | {|||}      |     \implies u(t) & = u_{0} e^{\lambda(t-t_{0})}
  89 | {|||}      |   \end{align*}
  90 | {|||}      | 
  91 | {|||}      | We are interested in the change over one year, so let $t_{0}=t$, so $u_{0}=u(t)$, and consider
  92 | {|||}      |   \begin{align*}
  93 | {|||}      |     u(t + 1) & = u(t)e^{\lambda(t + 1 - t)}  \\
  94 | {|||}      |     & = u(t)e^{\lambda}  \\
  95 | {|||}      |     \implies \frac{u(t+1)-u(t)}{u(t)} & = \frac{u(t)e^{\lambda} - u(t)}{u(t)}  \\
  96 | {|||}      |     & = e^{\lambda} - 1.
  97 | {|||}      |   \end{align*}
  98 | {|||}      | This is the proportional increase in population over one year, so the UN estimate tells us that
  99 | {|||}      |   \begin{align*}
 100 | {|||}      |     e^{\lambda} - 1 & = 0.0114 \qquad (\text{$1.14\%$ growth})  \\
 101 | {|||}      |     \implies \lambda & = \ln (1+ 0.0114) \approx 0.01133551
 102 | {|||}      |   \end{align*}
 103 | {|||}      | 
 104 | {|||}      | Hence
 105 | {|||}[     | \[
 106 | {|||}[     |  u(t) = u_{0} e^{0.01133551(t-t_{0})}
 107 | {|||}      | \]
 108 | {|||}      | \end{example}
